<div class='commentinfo comment_'>
2006-10-30 04:28:34 (2770 days ago)
<div id='contact-4648'><span class='name'>Ken Dubel</span><span class='send-message'><a href="/content/Contact/view/contactid/4648/display/detail/">Details</a></span></div> </div>
<div class='commentbox'>
1/2/2007 update: In addition to the tree, a rock tunnel has been cleaned out and is now a hazard at<br/>
higher flows. See http://coastals.org/forum/viewtopic.php?t=3116 and scroll down a bit for details.<br/>
================================== The USGS recalibrated the gauge stage / cfs relationship in<br/>
November of 2005. The river has run so seldom since then it took me this long to notice the<br/>
discrepancies. From what I can tell, for example, at USGS 2.6 feet what used to be 638 cfs is now<br/>
reported at 511 cfs. Seems like a minor difference but if your zero is 600 then it makes the<br/>
difference between a day at work and a day digging the Pass! </div>
</td>
</tr>
